channel.name: Failed to submit proof after migrate from snarkyjs to o1js.

messages.content:
Hello, I'm the author of [MinaCTF](https://minactf.xyz/), I'm trying to upgrade from snarkyjs to o1js, but I encounter following error:
```
Error: Failed to send transaction {
  statusCode: 200,
  statusText: `Couldn't send zkApp command: (Verification_failed (Invalid_proof "In progress"))`
}
```
I have no other modification except replace snarkyjs (0.11) to o1js (0.14), and code is available here: https://github.com/SutuLabs/MinaCTF
It's against the Berkeley network. I have no clue what this error's meaning.

Does anybody could point me a migration guide, or what this error is saying.

embeds.title: GitHub - SutuLabs/MinaCTF
embeds.description: Contribute to SutuLabs/MinaCTF development by creating an account on GitHub.

messages.content: I believe that on the new version, it creates a new verification key.  I don’t know if there is actually an upgrade path that would work or not.  Easiest thing would just be to deploy a brand new version of your app and update the links to the new address, if that’s an option
As the Berkeley network reset, so the contract is new deployed one. Anyway, let me deploy one more new to try.
I retried, still got this error, is there any chance the verification key would change even the contract code keep same?
Yes, the verification key is new since the version change.  That’s what I meant to say
I think we are talking different things, as my CTF challenge is providing user the opportunity to solve it, user have to compile the smart contract in their environment (or get a precompiled one).
If the behavior changed to every compilation produce different verification key, I believe this could be the big issue in o1js framework.
And I knew this before: the precompile capability is not in the roadmap, so I cannot precompile to keep verification key unchanged.
Pre-compilation has been released in the latest version of o1js, but I'm not sure if the API is fully exposed yet.

The error message comes from the graphQL endpoint, not trying to compile the app in browser.  What I _think_ is happening is you have a CTF contract already deployed that you built with snarkyJS 0.11, and now you want to compile a contract with o1js 0.14 on the UI.  The graphQL endpoint is telling you that the proof you compiled is not compatible with the one you deployed before.

I can't be 100% certain based on the info I have, but that seems likely to me.  It's not exactly a big issue in the framework because the framework is in a beta state, and nothing is meant to work long term.  Someday, these types of migrations will have to be handled better.

If you imagine that they release a new custom gate that does hashing more efficiently, they will probably replace the usage in `Poseidon.hash` to use that more efficient gate.  The same human-readable code will use a different gate, and thus a different circuit.  So when you compile the same code in a new version, you may be generating a new circuit, with a different verification key.

The CTF contract is generated during user request, not a permanent contract. So I constantly deploying new contracts, no old contract involved. As I upgrade both the contract dependencies, they should both used the latest o1js 0.14.

How can I verify if my deployed contract is in right version?
For precompile, what I can find is the information which gave no plan on precompile: https://discord.com/channels/484437221055922177/1070570936799084554/1070570936799084554
This is make sense, what I mean **big issue** is if I compile same contract twice yielding different verification key.

https://discord.com/channels/484437221055922177/915745847692636181/1175384263248584795

Check out this comment for the latest on pre-compiling. And the latest comments here: https://discord.com/channels/484437221055922177/1171938451193593856
In the repo you shared, both the contracts and UI folders have snarkyjs v0.11 right now.  Are you working off of a development branch?  Could you push it?
I'm quite sure the error is coming from the graphQL endpoint when you call `.send` on your zkapp.  It would help if I could see exactly where that's getting called.

I just pushed the code to [feat_o1js](https://github.com/SutuLabs/MinaCTF/tree/feat_o1js), you can find the whole working process by this recording: https://twitter.com/icerdesign/status/1689286599823986689

To reproduce the error:
1. start server/ui, through UI, start the `checkin` simple challenge, `Deploy` new challenge.
2. During `Capture` phase, `Download Project` to local, and open that project with dependency installation `npm i`, and run code by `npm start`. Here you will see the error mentioned in the main thread.
The server is externally depend on PocketBase, you can either simply comment the related code, or fire up a local PocketBase with this configured database file:
Idk what exactly the problem is.  I'd suggest simplifying to a minimum viable example to start.

One thing I noticed is in the source directory, `FLAG` is set to `export const FLAG = Number(process.env.FLAG ?? 111111);` and in the downloaded directory it's always `111111`.  Since that constant is locked into the circuit at compile time, making it a dynamic value shouldn't work.  Try making the flag a private input instead, so its not hard-coded into the circuit.

Between the two versions of o1js (7 and 14), there were breaking changes in Mina.transaction.

Try to use 
```typescript
function transaction(sender: FeePayerSpec, f: () => void): Promise<Transaction>;
```
instead of
```typescript
function transaction(f: () => void): Promise<Transaction>;
```
in https://github.com/SutuLabs/MinaCTF/blob/feat_o1js/ui/src/services/zkappWorker.ts#L56 and other lines with Mina.transaction, maybe it will help
That would be consistent with a vk mismatch, since in the first directory, the input is different than in the second (the value of `FLAG` differs)

This variable is for future-proof, currently, they are same, the downloaded source is always 111111 due to the programmatically generated during download. 
PS: the download isn't a true download, it is generating download package on-the-fly in the browser according to the parameter used in the smart contract.

Because before the upgrade(both the network and o1js), it works, so that's why I want to know what's the error mean and how to workaround it if any experience exists.
If we cannot simply get the root cause, maybe it takes time to dive into the o1js source code and preparing another minimum viable example.
Sorry for this misleading file, but this file is deprecated and no longer used by any function. Thanks for your suggestion anyway.

Is this file depreciated, too?
https://github.com/SutuLabs/MinaCTF/blob/feat_o1js/contracts/server/vkey.json
I think you may find the most important point👍 , let me take a closer look.

Here, you deploy the contract with the old verification key:
https://github.com/SutuLabs/MinaCTF/blob/feat_o1js/contracts/server/services/utils.ts#L49
Yes, it works, thank you! My fault, forget to update the keys.
